      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm working on my dissertation and i keep hitting a wall with my p-values. if i have a result that's at 0.06, why is that technically \"not significant\" even if the effect size looks pretty strong? it feels kind of arbitrary.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The threshold of $p < 0.05$ is a conventional benchmark used to control for Type I errors, meaning we are aiming to reject the null hypothesis when there is a genuine effect. A $p$-value of $0.06$ suggests that if there were truly no effect in the population, you would observe data this extreme 6% of the time, which is slightly higher than the 5% risk you set. While the effect size indicates practical importance, the $p$-value reflects statistical certainty based on your sample size and variability.",
