    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks that makes sense. but it feels like we're just ignoring something real because of a tiny margin. isn't it possible the \"lack of significance\" is just due to noise or random interference in the data rather than there actually being no effect?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are exactly right; a non-significant result can often be attributed to insufficient statistical power, meaning your sample size might be too small to detect a real effect. The $p$-value primarily tests the distribution of your sample data against the null hypothesis, but it doesn't quantify the strength of the evidence against that hypothesis if it's borderline. Considering effect sizes and confidence intervals alongside the $p$-value helps provide a more nuanced picture of potential real-world importance.",
      "source": "target",
