      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah i get the power thing. but when there's so much noise or outliers messing things up, it feels less like math and more like the data is just being chaotic for no reason. how do researchers actually distinguish between \"natural\" variability and something more systematic that's actually skewing the results?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Researchers use diagnostic tools like residual plots, box plots, and tests for normality to check for influential outliers and systematic patterns. Robust statistical methods, which are designed to be less sensitive to extreme values, can also help identify if noise is masking or driving the observed data. If the variance of the noise is extremely high relative to the signal, it suggests the issue is inherent data heterogeneity rather than a single systematic error.",
      "source": "target",
